f=Shared OS/logical/binet-field-effectiveness.md · in=Les Binet Peter Field's *The Long Short It* (2013) single important empirical work modern marketing effectiveness. Drawing IPA (Institute Practitioners Advertising) Effectiveness Databank **996 campaigns across 30+ years**, comprehensive marketing effectiveness database world Binet Field definitively answered question divided marketers decades: budgets split between short-term activation long-term brand building? Their answer, **60:40 rule**, reshaped global marketing practice. extraction operationalizes major finding spark's campaign-planning, rio's budget-allocation, kai's performance-measurement functions. · h2:FINDING 60:40 RULE Brand-Building vs. Activation=*Ch.1, pp.3-14; Ch.8, pp.67-74* · h3:The Core Finding="The optimal budget split approximately 60% brand-building 40% sales activation." (Ch.1, p.5) Binet Field analyzed IPA cases campaign objective broadly dividing campaigns designed drive immediate sales response ("activation") designed build long-term brand preference ("brand-building"). They correlated budget split long-term business effectiveness scores (profit, market share growth, pricing power). resulting efficiency curve showed clear optimum: **60:40** brand-building activation. Campaigns skewed heavily toward activation (>70%) achieved strong short-term results decayed rapidly. Campaigns skewed heavily toward brand-building (>80%) built strong brands under-invested converting equity sales. **The 60:40 sweet spot (Ch.1, pp.8-10):** "Brands allocated roughly 60% their budget brand-building 40% activation consistently achieved strongest long-term business results higher market share, greater profit growth, superior pricing power compared brands skewed either way." · h3:Short-Term vs. Long-Term Effects (Ch.2, pp.15-28)=\| Dimension \| Activation (Short-Term) \| Brand-Building (Long-Term) \| · h3:Short-Term vs. Long-Term Effects (Ch.2, pp.15-28)=\|-----------\|------------------------\|---------------------------\| · h3:Short-Term vs. Long-Term Effects (Ch.2, pp.15-28)=\| **Timeframe** \| Immediate — days to weeks \| Cumulative — months to years \| · h3:Short-Term vs. Long-Term Effects (Ch.2, pp.15-28)=\| **Effect curve** \| Sharp spike, rapid decay \| Slow build, sustained plateau \| · h3:Short-Term vs. Long-Term Effects (Ch.2, pp.15-28)=\| **Creative approach** \| Rational, product-focused, offer-driven \| Emotional, brand-focused, story-driven \| · h3:Short-Term vs. Long-Term Effects (Ch.2, pp.15-28)=\| **Metrics** \| Sales, conversion, click-through \| Awareness, salience, mental availability \| · h3:Short-Term vs. Long-Term Effects (Ch.2, pp.15-28)=\| **Budget share** \| 40% of spend \| 60% of spend \| · h3:Short-Term vs. Long-Term Effects (Ch.2, pp.15-28)=\| **Measurement window** \| 1-4 weeks post-campaign \| 6-24 months post-campaign \| · h3:Short-Term vs. Long-Term Effects (Ch.2, pp.15-28)=\| **Risk** \| Over-investment → brand erodes, pricing power drops \| Under-investment in activation → strong brand, weak sales conversion \| · h3:Two-Step Model (Ch.2, pp.20-24)=Binet Field propose two-step model marketing works: **Brand-building creates mental availability.** Through emotional, story-driven advertising, brand builds salience consumers' minds. consumer enters purchase situation, brand comes mind. **Activation converts mental availability sales.** Through rational, targeted, offer-driven marketing, brand converts "top mind" "in basket." critical insight: **you need BOTH.** brand activates (100% sales) gets sale today brand equity tomorrow. brand builds (100% brand) great reputation mechanism convert revenue. 60:40 balance empirically optimal mix. **Connection Ogilvy (ogilvy-creative-code.md):** Ogilvy's Brand Image Law (Ch.1, pp.18-20) anticipated finding years: "Every advertisement thought contribution complex symbol brand image." Ogilvy understood intuitively what Binet Field proved empirically: brand-building ads wasteful "awareness" they long-term investments compound. · h2:FINDING SHARE VOICE (SOV) EXCESS SHARE VOICE (ESOV)=*Ch.5, pp.47-56* · h3:Share Voice Definition (Ch.5, pp.47-50)="Share Voice (SOV) brand's advertising spend percentage total category advertising spend. reliable predictor market share change." (Ch.5, p.48) IPA data showed consistent relationship: · h3:Share Voice Definition (Ch.5, pp.47-50)=**SOV SOM (Share Market):** Brand GROW market share., **SOV SOM:** Brand MAINTAIN current market share., **SOV SOM:** Brand LOSE market share. · h3:Share Voice Definition (Ch.5, pp.47-50)=sometimes called "Jones's Law" after John Philip Jones (1990), whose earlier research first identified SOV-SOM relationship. Binet Field confirmed refined larger IPA dataset. · h3:ESOV Excess Share Voice (Ch.5, pp.51-55)=`ESOV = SOV - SOM \· where: \· SOV = Brand_Ad_Spend / Category_Total_Ad_Spend \· SOM = Brand_Market_Share / Total_Category_Sales` · h3:ESOV Excess Share Voice (Ch.5, pp.51-55)="ESOV SOV SOM. Positive ESOV predicts market share growth. brand needs approximately percentage points ESOV grow point market share year." **The ESOV formula (Ch.5, p.52):** **ESOV benchmarks IPA data (Ch.5, pp.53-55):** · h3:ESOV Excess Share Voice (Ch.5, pp.51-55)=\| Brand Size \| ESOV Needed for 1% Share Growth \| Typical Annual Growth Budget (as % of revenue) \| · h3:ESOV Excess Share Voice (Ch.5, pp.51-55)=\|-----------\|-------------------------------\|---------------------------------------------\| · h3:ESOV Excess Share Voice (Ch.5, pp.51-55)=\| **Small** (<5% share) \| ~5-8% ESOV per share point \| 15-25% of revenue \| · h3:ESOV Excess Share Voice (Ch.5, pp.51-55)=\| **Medium** (5-15% share) \| ~8-12% ESOV per share point \| 10-20% of revenue \| · h3:ESOV Excess Share Voice (Ch.5, pp.51-55)=\| **Large** (>15% share) \| ~12-15% ESOV per share point \| 5-15% of revenue \| · h3:ESOV Excess Share Voice (Ch.5, pp.51-55)=**The SOV-SOM equilibrium (Ch.5, p.54):** "In long run, market share trends toward share voice. you consistently out-spend your market share, you grow. you consistently under-spend, you shrink. exceptions IPA data." · h3:Size Advantage Paradox (Ch.5, pp.55-56)=Larger brands advantage: they afford larger absolute SOV. they face disadvantage: they need ESOV share point gained. creates "moat" effect large brands harder dislodge, harder grow. New entrants grow faster less ESOV sustain high spending they scale. · h3:Spark's Campaign Gate Checklist=campaign passing through spark's gate, evaluate against Binet Field criteria: · h3:Spark's Campaign Gate Checklist=\| # \| Criteria \| Citation \| Pass Condition \| · h3:Spark's Campaign Gate Checklist=\|---\|---------\|----------\|---------------\| · h3:Spark's Campaign Gate Checklist=\| 1 \| **60:40 budget split** \| Ch.1, p.5 \| At least 50% allocated to brand-building (allowable range: 50-70%) \| · h3:Spark's Campaign Gate Checklist=\| 2 \| **Emotional lead creative** \| Ch.4, p.37 \| Primary creative approach is emotional, not rational \| · h3:Spark's Campaign Gate Checklist=\| 3 \| **Creative commitment plan** \| Ch.7, p.59 \| Same core creative idea planned for 2+ years \| · h3:Spark's Campaign Gate Checklist=\| 4 \| **ESOV analysis** \| Ch.5, p.51 \| ESOV calculated and >0 for growth targets \| · h3:Spark's Campaign Gate Checklist=\| 5 \| **Long-term measurement** \| Ch.2, p.20 \| Brand metrics tracked 6-24 months post-campaign \| · h3:Spark's Campaign Gate Checklist=\| 6 \| **Activation bridge** \| Ch.2, p.24 \| Clear mechanism to convert brand equity into sales \| · h3:Budget Allocation Calculator (rio's tool brand_metrics.py)=campaign total budget · h3:Budget Allocation Calculator (rio's tool brand_metrics.py)=**Brand-building allocation (60%):** 0.60 emotional, story-driven, long-form content, sponsorships, brand campaigns, **Activation allocation (40%):** 0.40 performance ads, retargeting, offers, promotions, direct response · h3:Budget Allocation Calculator (rio's tool brand_metrics.py)=**Tactical split channel type (Binet Field, Ch.8, pp.79-82):** · h3:Budget Allocation Calculator (rio's tool brand_metrics.py)=\| Channel \| Primary Role \| Budget Source \| · h3:Budget Allocation Calculator (rio's tool brand_metrics.py)=\|---------\|-------------\|---------------\| · h3:Budget Allocation Calculator (rio's tool brand_metrics.py)=\| TV / Cinema \| Brand-building \| 60% allocation \| · h3:Budget Allocation Calculator (rio's tool brand_metrics.py)=\| Radio / Outdoor \| Brand-building (supporting) \| 60% allocation \| · h3:Budget Allocation Calculator (rio's tool brand_metrics.py)=\| Social Content \| Brand-building + Activation \| Split 60/40 \| · h3:Budget Allocation Calculator (rio's tool brand_metrics.py)=\| Search / Shopping \| Activation \| 40% allocation \| · h3:Budget Allocation Calculator (rio's tool brand_metrics.py)=\| Direct Mail / Email \| Activation \| 40% allocation \| · h3:Budget Allocation Calculator (rio's tool brand_metrics.py)=\| Sponsorship / PR \| Brand-building \| 60% allocation \| · h3:Budget Allocation Calculator (rio's tool brand_metrics.py)=\| Retail / Trade \| Activation \| 40% allocation \| · h2:BOUNDARIES WITH OTHER SCRIPTS=**brand_metrics.py:** Implements ESOV calculator, 60:40 budget allocator, share-of-voice calculator, campaign effectiveness scorer based IPA databank findings extraction., **marketing_laws.py:** Pareto principle Mere Exposure effect Law Diminishing Returns underpin Binet Field findings. Pareto: top 20% campaigns drive 80% effectiveness (the IPA data supports this). Mere Exposure: brand-building works through repeated, positive exposure. Diminishing Returns: activation spend diminishing returns curve; brand-building compounding curve., **aaker-brand-equity.md:** Brand-building (Binet Field) building Aaker's four brand equity dimensions. 60% brand-building budget investment brand equity., **ogilvy-creative-code.md:** Ogilvy's creative rules "how" brand-building 60%. Binet Field answer "how much"; Ogilvy answers "how.", **heath-made-to-stick.md:** SUCCESs provides creative design framework brand-building (Emotional, Stories, Unexpected) activation (Simple, Concrete, Credible).